ES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExchanges have always had more than economic significance: values circulate and encounters become institutionalized. This volume explores the changing meaning of the circulation of second-hand goods from the Renaissance to today, and thereby examines the blurring of boundaries between market, gifts, and charity. It describes the actors of the market - official entities such as corporations, recognized professions, and established markets but also the subterranean circulation that develops around the need for money. The complex layers that not only provide for numerous intermediaries but also include the many men and women who, as sellers or buyers, use these circulations on countless occasions are also examined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aSecondhand tradexHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aAgo, Renata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharpy, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeceulaer, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Laurence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoode, Jackie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJullien, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPietri, Valérie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorter Benson, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSandberg, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://i